🔄 CI/CD Life Cycle Explained

1. Code Commit
   Developer pushes code to GitHub.

This triggers the pipeline in Jenkins.

2. Build & Test
   Maven compiles the code.

Unit tests are executed to ensure functionality.

3. Code Quality & Security
   SonarQube performs static code analysis (quality checks).

Trivy scans for vulnerabilities in dependencies and container images.

A Quality Gate ensures only clean code passes forward.

4. Artifact Management
   Maven packages the application.

The artifact (e.g., .jar or .war) is stored in Nexus Repository for versioning and reuse.

5. Containerization
   Docker builds and tags the image.

The image is pushed to a registry for deployment.

6. Deployment
   Kubernetes orchestrates deployment of the Docker image.

Ensures scalability, load balancing, and resilience.

7. Monitoring & Feedback
   Prometheus collects metrics.

Grafana visualizes dashboards for performance monitoring.

Notifications (e.g., via email) alert developers about pipeline status.

8. Verification
   Deployment is verified to ensure the application is running correctly.

